but if you connect them with an

00:37:48.231 --> 00:37:51.043
electrical wire,
what happens is that the extra

00:37:51.043 --> 00:37:53.719
negative charges here will go to
that side,

00:37:53.719 --> 00:37:59.556
and then when you are done they
will both become electrically

00:37:59.556 --> 00:38:00.530
neutral.
 

00:38:00.530 --> 00:38:02.429
Okay, so that's why.
 

00:38:02.429 --> 00:38:06.036
So the point of this one is:
electric charges can flow

00:38:06.036 --> 00:38:09.440
through some materials,
but not other materials.

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:11.706
If it can flow through some
materials, it's called a

00:38:11.706 --> 00:38:12.239
conductor.
 

00:38:12.239 --> 00:38:15.269
If it cannot flow through them,
it's called an insulator.

00:38:15.269 --> 00:38:17.340
So real life you've got both.
 

00:38:17.340 --> 00:38:19.349
So when you're changing the
light bulb,

00:38:19.349 --> 00:38:21.943
if you don't want to get an
electric shock you're supposed

00:38:21.943 --> 00:38:24.809
to stand on a piece of wood
before you stick your finger in,

00:38:24.809 --> 00:38:26.789
unless you've got other
intentions.

00:38:26.789 --> 00:38:31.271
Then, you will find that you
don't get the shock because the

00:38:31.271 --> 00:38:33.929
